Wash and dry produce. Trim and slice @scallions{2%unit}, separating whites from greens. Peel and mince or grate @garlic{1%clove}.

Drizzle @cooking oil{2%teaspoon} in a hot #large pot{}. Add @ground pork{10%ounce} and scallion whites; season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until browned, ~{2%minutes} (it will finish cooking in Step 3).

To #pot{} with pork mixture, add @water{3 1/2%cups}, @chicken stock concentrate{2%unit}, @pork ramen stock concentrate{2%unit}, and half the @soy sauce{2%tablespoon} (7 cups water and all the soy sauce for 4); cover and bring to a simmer.

Meanwhile, in a #small microwave-safe bowl{}, mix @sesame seeds{1%tablespoon}, garlic, half the @sesame oil{1%tablespoon} (all for 4), a drizzle of oil, a big pinch of salt, and as many @chili flakes{1%teaspoon} as you like. Cover with #plastic wrap{} and microwave until fragrant, ~{30%seconds}.

Once broth is simmering, reduce heat under pot to medium. Add @ramen noodles{4.5%ounce}, @bok choy and napa cabbage{4%ounce}, and @spinach{5%ounce}; simmer, stirring, until noodles are tender and pork is cooked through, ~{2%minutes}. Taste and season with salt and pepper if desired.

Divide ramen between #large soup bowls{}. Stir in as much chili garlic oil as you like.

Top with scallion greens and a few @crispy fried onions{1%unit}. Serve.

> TIP: Don't add all the onions just yet! Add them as you eat to keep them nice and crispy.

> Ground Pork is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.